# The <canvas> Element üé®

The `<canvas>` element is used to draw graphics, on the fly, via JavaScript.

- The `<canvas>` element is only a container for graphics.
- You must use a script to actually draw the graphics.

```html
<canvas id="myCanvas" width="200" height="100"></canvas>
```

<!-- FULL_CODE_START
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>

<canvas id="myCanvas" width="200" height="100" style="border:1px solid #000000;">
Your browser does not support the HTML canvas tag.
</canvas>

<script>
var c = document.getElementById("myCanvas");
var ctx = c.getContext("2d");

// Draw a red line
ctx.moveTo(0, 0);
ctx.lineTo(200, 100);
ctx.stroke();

// Draw a blue circle
ctx.beginPath();
ctx.arc(95, 50, 40, 0, 2 * Math.PI);
ctx.strokeStyle = "blue";
ctx.stroke();
</script>

</body>
</html>
FULL_CODE_END -->

# Drawing on Canvas üñåÔ∏è

Common context methods:

- `getContext("2d")`: Returns an object that provides methods and properties for drawing on the canvas.
- `fillStyle`: Sets the color to fill the drawing.
- `fillRect(x, y, w, h)`: Draws a filled rectangle.

```js
var canvas = document.getElementById("myCanvas");
var ctx = canvas.getContext("2d");
ctx.fillStyle = "#FF0000";
ctx.fillRect(0, 0, 150, 75);
```

# Geolocation API üåç

The HTML Geolocation API is used to locate a user's position.

```js
function getLocation() {
  if (navigator.geolocation) {
    navigator.geolocation.getCurrentPosition(showPosition);
  } else {
    x.innerHTML = "Geolocation is not supported by this browser.";
  }
}
```

> üîí **Privacy:** Since this can compromise privacy, the position is not available unless the user approves it.

# Web Workers üë∑

A web worker is a JavaScript that runs in the background, independently of other scripts, without affecting the performance of the page.

Great for computationally expensive tasks.

```js
var w = new Worker("demo_workers.js");

w.onmessage = function(event) {
  document.getElementById("result").innerHTML = event.data;
};
```
